WEBVTT

00:14.392 --> 00:15.013
Is it running? It is running. Oh.

00:19.700 --> 00:24.407
This is Alan Vines. I want to start in or continue 
working on the period in which I was spending half

00:24.427 --> 00:39.049
time in Washington and half time in Woods Hole.

00:44.058 --> 01:04.999
The advent of

00:44.058 --> 01:04.999
better instrumentation and of more laboratories 
getting involved in oceanography

00:44.058 --> 01:04.999
was very important.

01:08.563 --> 01:13.828
Along about this time, Scripps got the RV Horizon. 
so they could start making expeditions

01:14.500 --> 01:23.732
with really a much better capability than 
Atlantis was ever able to. By this, they had a

01:25.274 --> 01:33.864
better choice of where they could go, how much they 
could carry, and so forth.

01:42.876 --> 01:43.917
All of the Of course, from where I sat in the working 
with the Bureau of Ships administering the

01:45.398 --> 02:15.034
laboratories, it seemed to me that the 
laboratories operated together and on a somewhat

01:45.398 --> 02:15.034
more

01:45.398 --> 02:15.034
centralized, not centralized plan, but the 
coordination was, it probably appeared better to

01:45.398 --> 02:15.034
me than it did to many other people because So much 
of it was being operated out of our desk. At that

02:22.357 --> 02:32.132
time, I would presume the budgets at Woods Hole 
were probably 80% from the Bureau of Ships. And at

02:32.632 --> 02:45.291
Scripps, which had a great deal more state 
financing, it was probably lower and down around

02:32.632 --> 02:45.291
60%.

02:46.722 --> 02:47.503
possibly 50%.

02:52.387 --> 03:14.367
During this period in the Woods Hole work, in our 
acoustic section, we were very heavily involved

02:52.387 --> 03:14.367
with

02:52.387 --> 03:14.367
convergent zone sonar and operated about

03:15.798 --> 03:19.021
five major tests a year. Brackett Hersey was in the 
acoustics work. Brackett Hersey was my boss at

03:25.468 --> 03:28.952
Woods Hole. He had taken over the acoustics and was 
chiefly responsible for the, deserves the

03:29.172 --> 03:43.307
principal credit for the high quality of 
acoustics work. trying to keep it much more

03:43.810 --> 03:48.855
quantitative, certainly, than I ever would have. 
Because I was more interested in the area,

03:50.076 --> 03:56.843
oceanographic aspects of the business. And 
Hersey was more interested

03:57.945 --> 04:10.037
and involved in maintaining better acoustic 
measurements and keeping information data that

04:10.743 --> 04:16.769
we got more creditable in the eyes of professional 
acousticians. That doesn't mean that either one

04:18.991 --> 04:29.781
of us were negligent of the other aspects of it, but 
that tended to be somewhat of an automatic

04:18.991 --> 04:29.781
division of labor.

04:34.365 --> 04:39.450
During this time, Islin was following the work 
very closely advice, kibitzing, and helping us

04:40.358 --> 04:53.759
out on a little bit better general interpretation 
of how the ocean worked. Also during this time, the

04:53.779 --> 05:07.800
Ewing and Warzel at the Lamont Laboratory, excuse 
me, at the Columbia Laboratory,

05:11.392 --> 05:20.021
heavily involved in the transmission problem 
largely as it came out of geophysics. And both

05:21.343 --> 05:35.158
Columbia and Woods Hole, largely through Hersey, 
were heavily involved in doing acoustical

05:21.343 --> 05:35.158
seismic tests and measurements. Most of this was 
between the United States and the Mid-Atlantic

05:40.417 --> 05:46.244
Ridge, because that was all the capability we had 
with our ships.

05:50.349 --> 05:59.980
At that time, most of the seismic operations were 
two-ship operations involving one ship for

05:50.349 --> 05:59.980
shooting and one ship for receiving.

06:01.762 --> 06:10.272
So the general attitude was to take Atlantis and 
whatever other ship we could get, and then as we

06:10.555 --> 06:20.243
acquired more smaller ships, such as the Bear and 
Karen, we had a wider variety of ships. But smaller

06:20.384 --> 06:28.130
ones were confined largely within the Great 
American Bight that is only out to Bermuda.

06:31.653 --> 06:39.280
One word about the kinds of ships that were small 
ships that were used then. Heaven knows they were

06:41.032 --> 06:45.817
as good as many of the boats that fishermen used. So 
from that standpoint, we weren't badly abused.

06:51.283 --> 06:57.070
But they were fairly small, running from 60 to 90 
feet. The amount of space on them was marginal,

06:58.491 --> 07:05.980
very marginal, from the standpoint of getting any 
reasonable amount of equipment aboard. Those

07:06.040 --> 07:08.963
that were sailing ships had booms and masts and 
stays in so many of the wrong places that they

07:09.871 --> 07:15.976
couldn't be used very efficiently. And

07:17.918 --> 07:31.950
while most of them were safe enough as far as 
getting back, the weather didn't have to get very

07:17.918 --> 07:31.950
heavy, but they got to where it was just plain 
impossible to continue the work. So the

07:32.131 --> 07:35.453
efficiency of these ships was not very high. And it 
is One of the reasons why, along about this time, I

07:38.930 --> 07:48.783
began to think much more that really the ship is the 
principal instrument. And it was going to be

07:50.505 --> 07:55.010
pretty hard for us to do better work than the ship 
was capable of. So I started spending much more

07:56.973 --> 08:08.768
time in the general concept of how can we improve 
ships, and how can we go about getting better ones.

08:11.607 --> 08:26.111
Didn't have to be very smart to do this because 
after you beat your brains out on inferior ships at

08:11.607 --> 08:26.111
sea, it looks like it's no good long-term solution 
for either you or the future of the game.

08:34.905 --> 08:36.207
By this time it was The general picture of the 
geology of the ocean was beginning to open up a good

08:38.768 --> 08:52.283
deal, the fact that there was a big lack of 
sediments in the ocean.

08:55.527 --> 09:07.020
The group at Columbia was the ringleader in this, 
but it was becoming apparent from work that many

08:55.527 --> 09:07.020
people were doing.

09:11.557 --> 09:25.392
ONR was moving along, picking up funding, and 
particularly the physical oceanography and

09:11.557 --> 09:25.392
biological end was doing very much more. But they 
were quite slow in working and financing problems

09:27.074 --> 09:33.180
on instrumentation. This tended to remain more in 
the Bureau of Ships budget

09:42.792 --> 09:49.461
10 or 15 years later in the history of 
oceanography, ONR was carrying the burden in

09:42.792 --> 09:49.461
instrumentation. And NSF was only hiring people 
or paying for ships. At the present time, it's

09:56.311 --> 10:00.817
getting to where nobody wants to pay for advanced 
instrumentation. And it is perhaps one reason

10:00.977 --> 10:11.652
why, at the moment, we may be on a little bit more of a 
technological plateau than is good for the

10:00.977 --> 10:11.652
science.

10:16.019 --> 10:26.653
Washington

10:16.019 --> 10:26.653
was, as always, I suppose, organizing into 
committees. There was a

10:26.833 --> 10:33.481
group established. I can't think of their name 
right now. In the oceanographic section, Dr.

10:36.485 --> 10:44.035
Redfield was the head of it, was the chairman of it. 
They held meetings around the country with

10:44.605 --> 10:54.299
representatives from the laboratories, trying 
to put a little more coherence into the

10:44.605 --> 10:54.299
oceanographic plans. This committee by itself 
did not really do a great deal of good, but it was

10:56.062 --> 11:12.165
useful in helping all laboratories get together 
and focus a little bit more communication between

11:12.888 --> 11:14.571
labs. And then, as it turned out, when the Korean 
War started, there was a little bit of a structure

11:15.312 --> 11:25.448
so that people knew who to talk to. There was a 
format in which advice could be sent around in a

11:25.489 --> 11:30.837
semi-official fashion.

11:34.724 --> 11:38.710
Lieutenant John Knauss, who was in the Office of 
Naval Research, He was there about a year or so

11:40.630 --> 11:47.159
while I was still at the Bureau of Ships. We spent a 
great deal of time together because John was a very

11:47.960 --> 11:58.955
alert young scientist who was disdained to go on in 
oceanography.

12:02.760 --> 12:07.887
Particularly, we had been shipmates on a trip that

12:10.533 --> 12:33.570
on the Atlantis, in which I was chief scientist 
down in the Cayman Trough operating out of

12:10.533 --> 12:33.570
Guantanamo, in which we were very much interested 
in the general current structure in the area south

12:10.533 --> 12:33.570
of Guantanamo as to how it might affect

12:10.533 --> 12:33.570
Navy tests in one way or another. But this 
particular night in Washington, a short time

12:35.103 --> 12:48.036
after the Korean War

12:35.103 --> 12:48.036
broke out officially. This was perhaps within the 
first day or second day. John and I made a list of the

12:54.323 --> 13:03.372
sorts of things that oceanography needed in 
preparation for for a much larger meeting the next

13:04.769 --> 13:07.652
day. I've tried to find this piece of paper because 
it was really kind of interesting. The principal

13:13.798 --> 13:24.489
things I can remember was that it was very clear 
that Woods Hole needed a building, needed more

13:13.798 --> 13:24.489
space.

13:28.714 --> 13:33.038
It was very clear that the Columbia people needed a 
ship. And it was very clear that Scripps needed

13:35.262 --> 13:39.590
more people. This has nothing to do with the 
quality of the people at Scripps. It was just

13:45.360 --> 13:54.175
merely that they had not built up as rapidly after 
the war as some of the other organizations. And

13:55.077 --> 13:59.565
while they were very strong in some aspects of 
oceanography,

14:02.144 --> 14:07.631
certainly needed more in the physical sense.

14:09.313 --> 14:21.728
One of the advantages of having done a little bit of 
homework is that sometimes it is surprisingly how

14:09.313 --> 14:21.728
rapidly some of the suggestions get okayed and 
executed. These

14:21.748 --> 14:31.560
Woods Hole did end up with their laboratory of 
oceanography, paid for by ONR, Columbia got

14:33.903 --> 14:50.447
enough more money and enough assurance to where 
Ewing could get the VEMA and then utilize the

14:33.903 --> 14:50.447
Atlantis as a secondary ship rather than as a 
primary ship. And without any question at all, the

14:51.509 --> 15:03.707
VEMA has been one of the great ships of America and 
of the oceanographic world in general in making

14:51.509 --> 15:03.707
the business global.

15:11.483 --> 15:41.001
After

15:11.483 --> 15:41.001
leaving Washington and coming back to Woods Hole 
for full time, although I still spent quite a bit of

15:11.483 --> 15:41.001
time in Washington, the research work that I was 
primarily concerned with remained the

15:11.483 --> 15:41.001
instrumentation problems having to do with 
salinity

15:11.483 --> 15:41.001
corrected sensors.

15:45.782 --> 16:00.439
I believe I mentioned earlier that Carl 
Schleicher and Bradshaw had been hired to do this,

15:45.782 --> 16:00.439
and they carried it on with quiet distinction. The 
other was variable depth sonar, and

16:11.305 --> 16:16.610
Starting about this time, the Navy began to get a 
few experimental units. And I spent a modest

16:17.451 --> 16:41.194
amount of time with the people in the fleet trying 
to sell it, write manuals for its use, and in

16:17.451 --> 16:41.194
general, try and help the Navy move in the 
direction of aerobatic sonar. However, the

16:43.351 --> 16:56.629
convergent zone sonar and working with submarine 
people continued to be the principal thing I was

16:43.351 --> 16:56.629
interested in. And about every two years, for a 
good many years, I started making a trip to Hawaii

16:57.750 --> 17:12.430
and working with comm sub pack to help them use 
submarines, underwater sound and so forth, a

17:12.832 --> 17:26.610
little more efficiently with submarines. This 
was a continuation of the work that I had done there

17:27.030 --> 17:30.815
during the war.

17:34.380 --> 17:40.948
Submarine specific fleet was in many respects an 
easier organization to work with than

17:41.502 --> 17:44.045
submarine's Atlantic fleet. Because they were so 
much further away, they weren't bothered by as

17:44.065 --> 17:48.389
many people. So when you did get out there, you 
found you generally got more cooperation. They

17:53.294 --> 17:57.438
hadn't already been worn out by a dozen people just 
like you.

18:01.783 --> 18:08.910
One of the other aspects was that the Pacific runs 
about half a mile deeper. Certainly the Hawaiian

18:09.262 --> 18:12.328
area has deep water close at hand. So many of the 
kinds of things we wanted to do, either for testing

18:12.428 --> 18:28.637
or demonstration, were much easier to do in local 
waters there than local waters off any of the

18:12.428 --> 18:28.637
submarine bases in continental United States.

18:37.021 --> 18:39.525
Why don't you shut it down for a while? Sure.

