I have a series of questions to ask about this 
period we're talking about right now. I have four

18:47.939 --> 18:52.827
questions, as a matter of fact, from both the 
previous tapes and this one. First of all, now that

18:52.847 --> 19:00.480
ONR is beginning to carry more than its share of 
research, What sort of oceanographers are they

19:01.220 --> 19:10.434
bringing into ONR, and whose policy is it to bring 
in what amounts to an oceanographer to work in an

19:01.220 --> 19:10.434
ONR desk with regularity?

19:17.404 --> 19:18.646
Well, Revell moved over there. I knew Revell went 
over there. Revell went over there. Then he got

19:21.771 --> 19:28.341
Gordon Lill as his right-hand man, who had been a 
bathymograph officer during the war. And then he

19:29.772 --> 19:31.514
got Art Maxwell. And this was the nucleus of their 
oceanographic group.

19:40.002 --> 19:54.876
And back when there were so few of them, and the 
general picture was

19:40.002 --> 19:54.876
people took positive attitudes instead of 
negative attitudes. Committees hadn't grown up

19:54.936 --> 19:56.278
yet. They had a great deal of of authority and 
exercise. Is this on? Yes. So that is my, I think

20:04.315 --> 20:10.321
that is the story of ONR. Then they started getting 
people, scientists from various laboratories,

20:10.341 --> 20:17.028
to come in and spend part time. This was very good 
because it brought fresh people in for a while. It

20:23.074 --> 20:24.535
also trained people. I believe, as I said earlier, 
I can't emphasize too much the importance of

20:25.662 --> 20:49.614
having some of our brightest young people, at 
least while they're still in the impressionable

20:25.662 --> 20:49.614
age, to get them into a group where they have to 
think about a lot more than just themselves or just

20:25.662 --> 20:49.614
their laboratory and start devoting more of their 
time to the profession as a whole. I think this was

20:51.075 --> 20:53.779
one of the reasons why Why so much occurred at that 
time. All right, now that anticipates my second

20:57.035 --> 20:59.598
question. Is the bringing in of these people to 
work halftime in Onora, is this primarily a

20:59.958 --> 21:06.065
training process on Onora's part? Does Ravel look 
upon this as a? Oh, I don't think this was a

21:09.009 --> 21:11.432
training. I think it was understood this would be 
one of the results of it. But it was primarily a

21:16.557 --> 21:22.264
question of how do you get talent there? 
oftentimes you'd bring people in who had

21:22.379 --> 21:27.626
specialties in a field that was real hot then. If 
they were going to be in an ocean expedition, then

21:29.188 --> 21:43.086
you might get people to come down who were somewhat 
more specialists or involved in that particular

21:29.188 --> 21:43.086
part of the work. So this rotation had a good deal to 
do oftentimes had a good deal to do with the trend of

21:49.514 --> 21:58.545
the research, which also was the trend of the 
money. Because oceanography really almost

21:59.486 --> 22:18.390
throughout its career, as I've known it, and

21:59.486 --> 22:18.390
particularly perhaps not quite so much now 
because we tend to have so many committees now, But

22:19.417 --> 22:26.487
there would be sort of a base load for 
oceanography, of which the budget could stand

22:19.417 --> 22:26.487
about so much. And this was generally for general 
purpose oceanography and for what you might call

22:28.449 --> 22:37.181
the highly organized oceanography. Then special 
problems would come up. For example, the

22:42.128 --> 22:46.133
discovery of convergent zone sonar was one. That 
probably shoved a 30% trenchant into the

22:46.552 --> 22:53.020
budgeting of money. And it allocated not 
narrowly, but at least broadly into one general

22:54.862 --> 23:01.431
field. With discussions of things like the Indian 
Ocean Expedition, which kicked around for a

23:03.854 --> 23:15.208
couple of years to see whether people thought it 
made sense, and many people Many people did not.

23:17.915 --> 23:20.759
But it was an idea that would sell. It was an idea 
that would keep the ships afloat, which is

23:20.819 --> 23:27.349
something the modern people have little 
comprehension about. If a laboratory only has one

23:27.389 --> 23:37.062
ship, and you only see it's budgeting for it a 
couple of months in advance, you think a lot harder

23:37.868 --> 23:49.448
about what can we do to get enough financing to 
where we can keep it going for a year or two at a time.

23:52.364 --> 23:56.510
I think the budgeting of oceanography, and I don't 
mean just the budgeting. I mean the way it worked,

23:56.550 --> 24:17.397
the way it brought in people, the way it sold 
itself, the way it convinced people that it was

23:56.550 --> 24:17.397
doing things, was to keep taking on programs, some 
of which were devised by individuals, others of

23:56.550 --> 24:17.397
which, say, the Indian Ocean was one. Because it 
was clear we knew very little about the Indian

24:17.418 --> 24:20.802
Ocean. I was not heavily involved in that except a 
little bit in the early planning. I did not go on any

24:25.364 --> 24:28.928
of those Indian Ocean expeditions. But our 
science knows so much more about the Indian Ocean

24:30.069 --> 24:43.062
because of that expedition, even though many 
people thought the original planning was very

24:30.069 --> 24:43.062
poor. It at least happened.

24:47.714 --> 24:58.628
I feel very strongly as a sort of a scientific 
thesis that Mother Nature puts out interesting

24:47.714 --> 24:58.628
things in white noise. It is unlikely

25:00.470 --> 25:04.976
to... It is so unlikely that we can have an ocean 
that is not interesting.

25:12.706 --> 25:14.869
The ocean bottom, for example, is... One of the 
reasons that I became interested in deep

25:15.929 --> 25:27.947
submersibles was discussions that the bottom of 
the ocean wasn't interesting just had to be wrong.

25:30.090 --> 25:38.703
One couldn't conceive that 100 million square 
miles of ocean bottom wasn't going to have some

25:30.090 --> 25:38.703
extremely interesting places. And any technique 
that would improve our ability to see find points

25:45.899 --> 25:47.301
was important. That next question? Sure. When do 
you begin to talk in the Bureau of Ships and ONR

25:51.885 --> 25:56.831
about the necessity for NSF? Oh, this kind of thing 
was all level way over my head. I was strictly a very

